  "prompt": "In what grade do American students learn topics like integral, derivatives, organic chemistry, and waves in detail?",
  "response": "In the United States, the typical progression of when students learn advanced topics like integrals, derivatives, organic chemistry, and waves varies depending on the school and the student's academic track. However, here\u2019s a general breakdown:\n\n1. **Integrals and Derivatives (Calculus)**:\n   - **Advanced Placement (AP) Calculus AB/BC**: These courses are typically taken in **11th or 12th grade** by students who have completed prerequisites like Algebra, Geometry, and Precalculus. Some advanced students may take Calculus as early as **10th grade**.\n   - **Non-AP Calculus**: Some schools offer Calculus in **12th grade** or as a dual-enrollment course with a local college.\n\n2. **Organic Chemistry**:\n   - **High School**: Organic chemistry is not a standard part of the high school curriculum. Most students encounter it for the first time in **college**, usually in their **second year** (sophomore year) as part of a chemistry or pre-med program.\n   - **Advanced High School Students**: Some high schools offer a brief introduction to organic chemistry as part of an **AP Chemistry** course, typically taken in **11th or 12th grade**, but it is not covered in detail.\n\n3. **Waves (Physics)**:\n   - **Regular Physics**: Waves are introduced in a general high school physics course, which is often taken in **9th or 10th grade**, depending on the school's curriculum.\n   - **AP Physics 1 or 2**: These courses, often taken in **11th or 12th grade**, cover waves in more depth, including topics like sound waves, light waves, and wave interference.\n\nIn summary:\n- **Calculus** is usually learned in **11th or 12th grade** (sometimes earlier).\n- **Organic Chemistry** is typically a college-level topic but may be briefly introduced in **AP Chemistry** in **11th or 12th grade**.\n- **Waves** are covered in **9th or 10th grade** (basic) and in more detail in **AP Physics** in **11th or 12th grade**.\n\nThese timelines can vary based on the student\u2019s academic path and school resources.",
